During a press briefing aboard Air Force One, White House spokesperson Karine Jean-Pierre provided details about President Biden's upcoming trip to Covington, Kentucky, where he will announce over $2 billion in investments from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law to upgrade the Brent Spence Bridge and other economically significant bridges across the country. The President will be joined by White House Infrastructure Coordinator Mitch Landrieu, Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, Senator Sherrod Brown, former Senator Rob Portman, Kentucky Governor Andy Beshear, and Ohio Governor Mike DeWine. Jean-Pierre also mentioned that Vice President Kamala Harris, Secretary of Transportation Pete Buttigieg, and Mayor Mitch Landrieu will be traveling to different parts of the country to highlight the President's economic plan and its impact on communities. Additionally, Jean-Pierre discussed the importance of bipartisan cooperation in passing the infrastructure law and the administration's commitment to ensuring transparency and accountability in the distribution of funds. The press briefing also touched on other topics, including the renomination of officials, the rejection of U.S. vaccines by China, and the upcoming anniversary of the January 6th Capitol attack.